rchivedate=June 20, 2017}}</ref><br /><ref name=\"Winners\">{{cite web|last1=Ramos|first1=Dino-Ray|title=Teen Choice Awards 2017 Winners: \u2018Wonder Woman\u2019, \u2018Beauty And The Beast\u2019, \u2018Riverdale\u2019 Among Honorees|url=https://deadline.com/2017/08/teen-choice-awards-winners-2017-wonder-woman-beauty-and-the-beast-riverdale-fox-1202147975/|website=Deadline Hollywood|publisher=enske Business Media, LLC.|date=August 13, 2017|accessdate=August 14, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170814101308/http://deadline.com/2017/08/teen-choice-awards-winners-2017-wonder-woman-beauty-and-the-beast-riverdale-fox-1202147975/|archivedate=August 14, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Teen Choice Award for Choice Movie Actor \u2013 Sci-Fi/Fantasy|Choice Movie: Fantasy Actor]]\n| Dan Stevens\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Teen Choice Award for Choice Movie Actress \u2013 Sci-Fi/Fantasy|Choice Movie: Fantasy Actress]]\n| Emma Watson\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Teen Choice Award for Choice Movie Villain|Choice Movie Villain]]\n| Luke Evans\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Choice Movie Ship\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Emma Watson and Dan Stevens\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Choice Liplock\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Choice Scene Stealer\n| Josh Gad\n| {{nom}}\n|- \n| rowspan=\"2\"| Choice Hissy Fit\n| Luke Evans\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Dan Stevens\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[16th Visual Effects Society Awards|Visual Effects Society Awards]]\n| February 13, 2018\n| Outstanding Virtual Cinematography in a Photoreal Project\n| Shannon Justison, Casey Schatz, Neil Weatherley and Claire Michaud for \"[[Be Our Guest]]\"\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/2018-visual-effects-society-awards-nominations-list-full-1067888|title=Visual Effects Society Awards: 'Apes,' 'Blade Runner 2049' Lead Feature Nominees|work=Hollywood Reporter|first=Carolyn|last=Giardina|date=January 16, 2018|accessdate=January 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180116220634/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/2018-visual-effects-society-awards-nominations-list-full-1067888|archive-date=January 16, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"| [[Washington D.C. Area Film Critics Association Awards 2017|Washington D.C. Area Film Critics Association]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| December 8, 2017\n| Best Motion Capture Performance\n| Dan Stevens\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dcfilmcritics.com/awards/|title=The 2017 WAFCA Awards|work=[[Washington D.C. Area Film Critics Association]]|date=December 7, 2017|accessdate=December 6, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312055647/http://www.dcfilmcritics.com/awards/|archivedate=March 12, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Production Design\n| Sarah Greenwood and Katie Spencer\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Women Film Critics Circle]]\n| December 17, 2017\n| Best Family Film\n| ''Beauty and the Beast''\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web|title=The 2017 Women Film Critics Circle (WFCC) Nominations|url=https://www.nextbestpicture.com/latest/the-2017-women-film-critics-circle-wfcc-nominations|last=Neglia|first=Matt|accessdate=December 13, 2017|date=December 12, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213010140/https://www.nextbestpicture.com/latest/the-2017-women-film-critics-circle-wfcc-nominations|archivedate=December 13, 2017}}</ref><br /><ref>{{cite web|title=The 2017 Women Film Critics Circle (WFCC) Winners|url=https://www.nextbestpicture.com/latest/the-2017-women-film-critics-circle-wfcc-winners|last=Neglia|first=Matt|accessdate=December 25, 2017|date=December 22, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226130500/https://www.nextbestpicture.com/latest/the-2017-women-film-critics-circle-wfcc-winners|archivedate=December 26, 2017}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Controversies==\n===Gay character===\nControversy erupted after director [[Bill Condon]] said there was a \"gay moment\" in the film, when LeFou briefly waltzes with Stanley, one of Gaston's friends.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/entertainthis/2017/03/20/beauty-and-the-beast-gay-moment-audience-reaction/99407168/ |title='Beauty and the Beast's 'gay moment' may have been much ado about nothing |newspaper=USA Today |date=March 20, 2017 |accessdate=March 21, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170910204317/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/entertainthis/2017/03/20/beauty-and-the-beast-gay-moment-audience-reaction/99407168/ |archivedate=September 10, 2017  }}</ref> Afterwards in an interview with [[Vulture.com]], Condon stated, \"Can I just say, I'm sort of sick of this. Because you've seen the movie\u2014it's such a tiny thing, and it's been overblown.\" Condon also added that ''Beauty and the Beast'' features much more diversity than just the highly talked-about LeFou: \"That was so important. We have interracial couples\u2014this is a celebration of everybody's individuality, and that's what's exciting about it.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2017/03/bill-condon-on-directing-beauty-and-the-beast.html |title=Bill Condon on Beauty and the Beast, His Musical Influences, and Lindsay Lohan's Plan for The Little Mermaid |publisher=Vulture |date=March 15, 2017 |accessdate=March 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170419051553/http://www.vulture.com/2017/03/bill-condon-on-directing-beauty-and-the-beast.html |archivedate=April 19, 2017  }}</ref> GLAAD president and CEO Sarah Kate Ellis praised the move, stating, \"It is a small moment in the film, but it is a huge leap forward for the film industry.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/glaad-beauty-and-the-beast-gay-moment-disney/|title=GLAAD president: \"Beauty and the Beast\" foes are \"outliers\"|author=Ned Ehrbar|publisher=CBS News|date=March 17, 2017|accessdate=March 17, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170419051558/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/glaad-beauty-and-the-beast-gay-moment-disney/|archivedate=April 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn Russia, [[Vitaly Milonov]] agitated the culture minister for banning the film,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/global/russia-ban-beauty-and-the-beast-josh-gad-gay-lefou-1202002198/ |title=Russia May Ban Disney's 'Beauty and the Beast' Over Gay Character |work=Variety |date=March 4, 2017 |accessdate=March 5, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170304203350/http://variety.com/2017/film/global/russia-ban-beauty-and-the-beast-josh-gad-gay-lefou-1202002198/ |archivedate=March 4, 2017  }}</ref> but instead it was given a 16+ rating (children under the age of 16 can only be admitted to see it in theaters with accompanying adults).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/03/06/beauty-and-the-beast-russia-lawmaker-ban/ |title=Russia won't ban Beauty and the Beast\u2014but will have an age restriction |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=March 6, 2017 |accessdate=March 7, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170910205642/http://ew.com/movies/2017/03/06/beauty-and-the-beast-russia-lawmaker-ban/ |archivedate=September 10, 2017  }}</ref> Additionally, a theater in [[Henagar, Alabama]] did not screen the film because of the subplot.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/beauty-and-the-beast-alabama-theater_us_58b9a6f7e4b05cf0f400427b |title=Alabama Theater Won't Show 'Beauty and the Beast' Because of Gay Subplot |work=The Huffington Post |accessdate=March 3, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170306104238/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/beauty-and-the-beast-alabama-theater_us_58b9a6f7e4b05cf0f400427b |archivedate=March 6, 2017  }}</ref> In [[Malaysia]], the [[Film Censorship Board of Malaysia|Film Censorship Board]] insisted the \"gay moment\" scene be cut, prompting an indefinite postponement of its release by Disney, followed by their decision to withdraw it completely if it could not be released uncensored.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2017/03/13/beauty-and-the-beast-release-postponed-for-internal-review/|title=Beauty and the Beast release postponed for 'internal review'|last=Cheang|first=Michael|date=March 13, 2017|accessdate=March 15, 2017|website=The Star Online|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170314040844/http://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2017/03/13/beauty-and-the-beast-release-postponed-for-internal-review/|archivedate=March 14, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/beauty-and-the-beast/news/a823340/disney-pulls-beauty-and-the-beast-from-cinemas-in-malaysi-until-further-notice/ |title=Disney pulls Beauty and the Beast from cinemas in Malaysia 'until further notice' |website=Digital Spy |date=March 13, 2017 |accessdate=March 13, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170910204933/http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/beauty-and-the-beast/news/a823340/disney-pulls-beauty-and-the-beast-from-cinemas-in-malaysi-until-further-notice/ |archivedate=September 10, 2017  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Disney refuses to cut 'gay moment' from 'Beauty and the Beast' for Malaysia|website=Malay Mail Online|accessdate=March 15, 2017|date=March 15, 2017|url=http://www.themalaymailonline.com/malaysia/article/disney-refuses-to-cut-gay-moment-from-beauty-and-the-beast-for-malaysia|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170910205012/http://www.themalaymailonline.com/malaysia/article/disney-refuses-to-cut-gay-moment-from-beauty-and-the-beast-for-malaysia|archivedate=September 10, 2017}}</ref> The studio moved the release date to March 30, to allow more time for Malaysia's censor board to make a decision on whether or not to release the film without changes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/disney-wont-cut-beauty-beast-gay-moment-malaysia-censors-986609|title=Disney Defies Malaysia Censors, Won't Cut 'Beauty and the Beast' Gay Moment|author=Mia Galuppo|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=March 15, 2017|accessdate=March 16, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170910205050/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/disney-wont-cut-beauty-beast-gay-moment-malaysia-censors-986609|archivedate=September 10, 2017}}</ref> The distributors and producers then submitted an appeal to the Film Appeal Committee of Malaysia, which allowed the film to be released without any cuts and a [[Film censorship in Malaysia#Rating system|P13 rating]] on the grounds that \"the gay element was minor and did not affect the positive elements featured in the film\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/malaysia-clears-release-beauty-beast-gay-moment-intact-report-987588|title=Malaysia Clears Release of 'Beauty and the Beast,' with 'Gay Moment' Intact|author=Patrick Brzeski|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=March 21, 2017|accessdate=March 21, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170910205127/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/malaysia-clears-release-beauty-beast-gay-moment-intact-987588|archivedate=September 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2017/03/29/film-appeals-committee-decision-to-release-beauty-and-beast/|title=Film Appeal Committee's decision to release Beauty and the Beast|newspaper=The Star Online|date=March 21, 2017|accessdate=March 30, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170910205221/http://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2017/03/29/film-appeals-committee-decision-to-release-beauty-and-beast/|archivedate=September 10, 2017}}</ref> In [[Kuwait]], the movie was withdrawn from cinemas by [[Cinescape|National Cinema Company]] which owns most of the cinemas in the country. A board member of the company stated that the Ministry of Information's censorship department had requested it to stop its screening and edit it for things deemed offensive by it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-39337844|title=Beauty and the Beast pulled from cinemas in Kuwait|publisher=BBC|date=March 21, 2017|accessdate=March 30, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328145707/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-39337844|archivedate=March 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe film also received criticism over its portrayal of LeFou, as many felt that it was used as a way of teasing LGBT+ viewers without providing adequate representation, with his \"exclusively gay moment\" being three seconds of him dancing with another man at the end of the film.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://screenrant.com/beauty-beast-power-rangers-gay-representation/|title=How Beauty and the Beast & Power Rangers Cheated Gay Fans|date=April 2, 2017|work=Screen Rant|access-date=October 21, 2017|language=en-US|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171021111628/http://screenrant.com/beauty-beast-power-rangers-gay-representation/|archivedate=October 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Belle and the Beast's relationship===\nDisney has sought to portray Belle as an empowered young woman,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Watkins|first1=Gwynne|title='Beauty and the Beast' Featurette Makes a Case for Feminist Belle|url=https://www.yahoo.com/movies/beauty-and-the-beast-featurette-makes-a-case-for-feminist-belle-180620182.html|accessdate=March 26, 2017|publisher=Yahoo Movies|date=March 2, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170419051635/https://www.yahoo.com/movies/beauty-and-the-beast-featurette-makes-a-case-for-feminist-belle-180620182.html|archivedate=April 19, 2017}}</ref> but a debate questioning whether it is possible for a captor to fall in love with their prisoner, and whether this is a problematic theme, has resulted.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Williams|first1=Zoe|title=Beauty and the Beast: feminist or fraud|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/mar/19/beauty-and-the-beast-feminist-or-fraud|accessdate=March 26, 2017|newspaper=The Guardian|date=March 19, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170419051751/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/mar/19/beauty-and-the-beast-feminist-or-fraud|archivedate=April 19, 2017}}</ref> As was the case with the original animated film, one argument is that Belle suffers from [[Stockholm syndrome]] (a condition that causes hostages to develop a psychological alliance with their captors as a survival strategy during captivity). Emma Watson studied whether Belle is trapped in an abusive relationship with the Beast before signing on and concluded that she does not think the criticism fits this version of the folk tale.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Blasberg|first1=Derek|title=Cover Story: Emma Watson, Rebel Belle|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/02/emma-watson-cover-story|accessdate=March 27, 2017|work=Vanity Fair|date=February 28, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170228194205/http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/02/emma-watson-cover-story|archivedate=February 28, 2017}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=August 2018}}<ref>{{cite news|last1=Breznican|first1=Anthony|title=Beauty and the Beast: Emma Watson addresses questions over Beast relationship|url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/02/16/beauty-and-the-beast-emma-watson-belle-beast-relationship/|accessdate=March 26, 2017|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=February 16, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170910210130/http://ew.com/movies/2017/02/16/beauty-and-the-beast-emma-watson-belle-beast-relationship/|archivedate=September 10, 2017}}</ref> Watson described Stockholm Syndrome as \"where a prisoner will take on the characteristics of and fall in love with the captor. Belle actively argues and disagrees with [Beast] constantly. She has none of the characteristics of someone with Stockholm Syndrome because she keeps her independence, she keeps that freedom of thought\", also adding that Belle defiantly \"gives as good as she gets\" before forming a friendship and romance with the Beast.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/02/16/beauty-and-the-beast-emma-watson-belle-beast-relationship/ |title=Beauty and the Beast: Emma Watson addresses questions over Beast relationship |accessdate=August 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170910210130/http://ew.com/movies/2017/02/16/beauty-and-the-beast-emma-watson-belle-beast-relationship/ |archivedate=September 10, 2017  }}</ref>\n\nPsychiatrist [[Frank Ochberg]], who was responsible for defining the term \"Stockholm syndrome\", said he does not think Belle exhibits the trauma symptoms of prisoners suffering from the syndrome because she does not go through a period of feeling that she is going to die.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Watkins|first1=Gwynne|title=Does Belle From 'Beauty and the Beast' Suffer From Stockholm Syndrome? We Asked an Expert.|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/does-belle-from-beauty-and-the-beast-suffer-from-stockholm-syndrome-we-asked-an-expert-175449990.html|accessdate=March 26, 2017|publisher=Yahoo Movies|date=March 20, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170910210202/https://www.yahoo.com/news/does-belle-from-beauty-and-the-beast-suffer-from-stockholm-syndrome-we-asked-an-expert-175449990.html|archivedate=September 10, 2017}}</ref> Some therapists, while acknowledging that the pairing's relationship does not meet the clinical definition of Stockholm syndrome, argue that the relationship depicted is dysfunctional and abusive and does not model healthy romantic relationships for young viewers.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Durvasula|first1=Ramani|title=Does Belle from Beauty and The Beast Have Stockholm Syndrome?|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5zyYzdsmeBU|accessdate=March 26, 2017|publisher=Screen Junkies|date=March 23, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170407104600/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5zyYzdsmeBU|archivedate=April 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Simon|first1=Rachel|title=The 'Beauty and the Beast' Relationship Isn't \"Stockholm Syndrome,\" No Matter How Screwed Up It May Be|url=https://www.bustle.com/p/the-beauty-the-beast-relationship-isnt-stockholm-syndrome-no-matter-how-screwed-up-it-may-be-44217|accessdate=March 26, 2017|magazine=Bustle|date=March 16, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170910210257/https://www.bustle.com/p/the-beauty-the-beast-relationship-isnt-stockholm-syndrome-no-matter-how-screwed-up-it-may-be-44217|archivedate=September 10, 2017}}</ref> Following this viewpoint, Constance Grady of [[Vox (website)|Vox]] wrote that [[Jeanne-Marie Leprince de Beaumont]]'s ''Beauty and the Beast'' was a fairy tale originally written to prepare young girls in 18th-century France for [[arranged marriage]]s, and that the power disparity is amplified in the Disney version.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Grady|first1=Constance|title=Is Beauty and the Beast \"a tale as old as Stockholm syndrome\"? Depends how you read it.|url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2017/3/23/15000768/beauty-and-the-beast-feminist-stockholm-syndrome|accessdate=March 26, 2017|publisher=Vox|date=March 23, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170910210439/https://www.vox.com/culture/2017/3/23/15000768/beauty-and-the-beast-feminist-stockholm-syndrome|archivedate=September 10, 2017}}</ref> Additionally, Anna Menta of ''[[Elite Daily]]'' argued that the Beast does not apologize to Belle for imprisoning, hurting, or manipulating her, and that his treatment of Belle is not painted as wrong.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Menta|first1=Anna|title=The 'Beauty and the Beast' Love Story Doesn't Hold Up To Emma Watson's Feminism|url=http://elitedaily.com/entertainment/film/beauty-and-the-beasts-abusive-relationship-emma-watson/1828119/|accessdate=March 26, 2017|website=Elite Daily|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170910210528/http://elitedaily.com/entertainment/film/beauty-and-the-beasts-abusive-relationship-emma-watson/1828119/|archivedate=September 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Future==\n===Potential follow-up film===\nShortly after the release of the film, [[Sean Bailey]] said that [[Walt Disney Pictures]] will \"explore possible [live-action] spin-off and prequel scenarios\" for animated and live-action Disney films, including ''Beauty and the Beast''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/03/beauty-and-the-beast-sean-bailey-disney-emma-watson-1202047710/|title=Sean Bailey On How Disney's Live-Action Division Found Its 'Beauty and the Beast' Mojo|website=Deadline|date=March 21, 2017|first=Mike|last=Fleming Jr.|access-date=April 28, 2019|archive-url=https://archive.li/20170910100558/http://deadline.com/2017/03/beauty-and-the-beast-sean-bailey-disney-emma-watson-1202047710/|archive-date=September 10, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Both [[Dan Stevens]] and [[Emma Watson]] expressed interest in reprising their roles in potential sequel or prequel to the film.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/beauty-and-the-beast-sequel-dan-stevens-sex-comedy-permission-tribeca-1202393018/|title=Dan Stevens on 'Beauty and the Beast' Sequel Talk, Tribeca Sex Comedy 'Permission'|magazine=Variety|date=April 22, 2017|first=Ramin|last=Setoodeh|access-date=April 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430124608/https://variety.com/2017/film/news/beauty-and-the-beast-sequel-dan-stevens-sex-comedy-permission-tribeca-1202393018/|archive-date=April 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/1830510/emma-watson-brought-up-a-potential-beauty-and-the-beast-sequel-idea-again|title=Emma Watson Brought Up A Potential Beauty and the Beast Sequel Idea Again|website=Cinema Blend|date=January 9, 2018|first=Adam|last=Holmes|access-date=April 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190428043706/https://www.cinemablend.com/news/1830510/emma-watson-brought-up-a-potential-beauty-and-the-beast-sequel-idea-again|archive-date=April 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Spin-off/prequel series===\nOn March 6, 2020, it was reported that [[ABC Signature Studios]] is developing a prequel limited series to the film focused on Gaston and LeFou, for [[Disney+]].<ref name=\"Disney+Series\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/beauty-beast-prequel-series-works-at-disney-1282859|title='Beauty and the Beast' Prequel Series in the Works at Disney+ (Exclusive)|date=March 6, 2020|first=Lesley|last=Goldberg|access-date=March 7, 2020m|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Luke Evans]] and [[Josh Gad]] will reprise their roles from the film, and will executive-produce the series alongside [[Eddy Kitsis]] and [[Adam Horowitz]], with Gad, Kitsis and Horowitz serving as showrunners and writers for the series.<ref name=\"Disney+Series\"/> [[Alan Menken]] was reported to be in talks to return as composer for the series.<ref name=\"Disney+Series\"/> Menken confirmed his involvement on April 2, 2020.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dTv0Sc4TPRE Talk Back with Alan Menken (2020)]</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{official website|http://movies.disney.com/beauty-and-the-beast-2017}}\n*{{IMDb title|2771200}}\n*{{Rotten Tomatoes|beauty_and_the_beast_2017|Beauty and the Beast}}\n*{{Box Office Mojo|beautyandthebeast2017}}\n*{{AllMovie title|601458}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title=''Beauty and the Beast''|state=collapsed\n|list1=\n{{Beauty and the Beast}}\n{{Disney's Beauty and the Beast}}\n{{Disney Princess}}\n{{Disney's live-action adaptations of animated franchises}}\n{{Alan Menken|state=collapsed}}\n{{Howard Ashman|state=collapsed}}\n{{Tim Rice|state=collapsed}}\n{{Bill Condon}}\n{{Stephen Chbosky}}\n{{MTV Movie Award for Best Movie}}\n}}\n{{Portal bar|Disney|Film|United States}}\n\n[[Category:2017 films]]\n[[Category:2017 3D films]]\n[[Category:2010s musical fantasy films]]\n[[Category:2010s romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s romantic fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American 3D films]]\n[[Category:American fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:American musical fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:American romantic fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American romantic musical films]]\n[[Category:Beauty and the Beast (franchise)]]\n[[Category:Censored films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Disney film remakes]]\n[[Category:Films featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:Films about curses]]\n[[Category:Films about royalty]]\n[[Category:Films about shapeshifting]]\n[[Category:Films based on adaptations]]\n[[Category:Films based on Beauty and the Beast]]\n[[Category:Films based on multiple works]]\n[[Category:Films based on works by Linda Woolverton]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Alan Menken]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Bill Condon]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 18th century]]\n[[Category:Films set in castles]]\n[[Category:Films set in France]]\n[[Category:Films shot at Shepperton Studios]]\n[[Category:Films using computer-generated imagery]]\n[[Category:American historical romance films]]\n[[Category:IMAX films]]\n[[Category:Mandeville Films films]]\n[[Category:Motion capture in film]]\n[[Category:Film remakes]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Evan Spiliotopoulos]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Stephen Chbosky]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Pictures films]]\n[[Category:American historical musical films]]\n", "name_user": "Tanishka017", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beauty_and_the_Beast_(2017_film)"}
{"title_page": "Vietnamese phonology", "text_new": "{{selfref|For assistance with IPA transcriptions of Vietnamese for Wikipedia articles, see [[Help:IPA/Vietnamese]].}}\n{{IPA notice}}\nThis article is a technical description of the sound system of the [[Vietnamese language]], including [[phonetics]] and [[phonology]]. Two main varieties of Vietnamese, [[Hanoi]] and [[Ho Chi Minh City]] (Saigon), are described below.\n\n==Initial consonants==\nInitial consonants which exist only in the Hanoi dialect are in red, while those that exist only in the Saigon dialect are in blue.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|- style=\"font-size: 90%;\"\n! colspan=\"2\" width=25% |\n! width=10% | [[Labial consonant|Labial]]\n! width=10% | [[Dental consonant|Dental]]/<br>[[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]]\n! width=10% | [[Postalveolar consonant|Retroflex]]\n! width=10% | [[Palatal consonant|Palatal]]\n! width=10% | [[Velar consonant|Velar]]\n! width=10% | [[Glottal consonant|Glottal]]\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Nasal consonant|Nasal]]\n| {{IPA link|m}}\n| {{IPA link|n}}\n|\n| {{IPA link|\u0272}}\n| {{IPA link|\u014b}}\n|\n|-\n! rowspan=\"3\" | [[Stop consonant|Stop]]/<br>[[Affricate consonant|Affricate]]\n! <small>[[Tenuis consonant|tenuis]]</small>\n| ({{IPA link|p}})\n| {{IPA link|t}}\n| style=\"background-color: #ccf\" | {{IPA link|\u0288}}\n| {{IPA link|c}}\n| {{IPA link|k}}\n| ({{IPA link|\u0294}})\n|-\n! <small>[[Aspirated consonant|aspirated]]</small>\n|\n| {{IPA|t\u02b0}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! <small>[[Glottalization|glottalized]]</small>\n| {{IPA link|\u0253}}\n| {{IPA link|\u0257}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[Fricative consonant|Fricative]]\n! <small>[[Voicelessness|voiceless]]</small>\n| {{IPA link|f}}\n| {{IPA link|s}}\n| style=\"background-color: #ccf\" | {{IPA link|\u0282}}\n|\n| {{IPA link|x}}\n| {{IPA link|h}}\n|-\n! <small>[[Voice (phonetics)|voiced]]</small>\n| style=\"background-color: #fcc\" | {{IPA link|v}}\n| {{IPA link|z}}~{{IPA link|j}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA link|\u0263}}\n|\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Approximant consonant|Approximant]]\n|\n| {{IPA link|l}}\n|\n|\n| {{IPA link|w}}\n|\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Rhotic consonant|Rhotic]]\n|\n| style=\"background-color: #ccf\" | {{IPA|r}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n* /w/ is the only initial consonant permitted to form [[consonant cluster]]s with other consonants.\n* {{IPA|/p/}} occurs syllable-initially only in [[loan word]]s, and is mostly converted into {{IPA|/\u0253/}} (as in ''s\u00e2m banh'', derived from French ''champagne'').\n* The glottalized stops are preglottalized and voiced:  {{IPA|[\u0294\u0253, \u0294\u0257]}} (the [[glottis]] is always closed before the oral closure). This glottal closure is often not released before the release of the oral closure, resulting in the characteristic [[implosive]] pronunciation. However, sometimes the glottal closure is released prior to the oral release in which case the stops are pronounced {{IPA|[\u0294b, \u0294d]}}. Therefore, the primary characteristic is preglottalization with implosion being secondary.\n* {{IPA|/\u0253, m/}} are [[Bilabial consonant|bilabial]], while {{IPA|/f, v/}} are [[Labiodental consonant|labiodental]].\n* {{IPA|/t, t\u02b0/}} are [[Denti-alveolar consonant|denti-alveolar]] ({{IPA|[t\u032a, t\u032a\u02b0]}}), while {{IPA|/\u0257, n, l/}} are [[Apical consonant|apico]]-[[alveolar consonant|alveolar]].<ref name=\"Kirby 382\">{{Harvcoltxt|Kirby|2011|p=382}}</ref>\n* {{IPA|/c, \u0272/}} are phonetically [[Laminal consonant|lamino]]-[[palatoalveolar]]  (the blade of the tongue makes contact behind the [[alveolar ridge]]).\n* {{IPA|/\u0288, c/}} are often slightly [[affricate]]d {{IPA|[\u0288\u0361\u0282, t\u0361\u0255]}}, but they are [[Aspiration (phonetics)|unaspirated]].\n* A [[glottal stop]] {{IPA|[\u0294]}} is inserted before words that begin with a vowel or {{IPA|/w/}}:\n\n:{| cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"line-height: 1.0em;\"\n| ''\u0103n''\n| 'to eat'\n| {{IPA|/\u0103n/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0294\u0103n]}}\n|-\n| ''u\u1ef7''\n| 'to delegate'\n| {{IPA|/wi/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0294wi]}}\n|}\n\n===Hanoi initials===\n* ''d'', ''gi'' and ''r'' are all pronounced {{IPA|/z/}}.\n* ''ch'' and ''tr'' are both pronounced {{IPA|/c/}}, while ''x'' and ''s'' are both pronounced {{IPA|/s/}}.\n* Some rural speakers merge {{IPA|/l/}} and {{IPA|/n/}} into {{IPA|/l/}}, although this is not considered standard.<ref name=\"Kirby 382\"/>\n\n===Saigon initials===\n* ''d'' and ''gi'' are both pronounced {{IPA|/j/}}.\n* Historically, {{IPA|/v/}} is pronounced {{IPA|[j]}} in common speech, merging with ''d'' and ''gi''. However, it is becoming distinct and pronounced as {{IPA|[v]}}, especially in careful speech. In traditional performance including C\u1ea3i l\u01b0\u01a1ng, \u0110\u1eddn ca t\u00e0i t\u1eed, H\u00e1t b\u1ed9i and some old speakers of Overseas Vietnamese, it is pronounced as consonant cluster [bj], [\u03b2j] or [vj].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Thompson|first=Laurence C.|date=1959-07|title=Saigon Phonemics|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/411232?origin=crossref|journal=Language|volume=35|issue=3|pages=454|doi=10.2307/411232}}</ref>\n* Historically, a distinction is made between ''ch'' {{IPA|/c/}} and ''tr'' {{IPA|/\u0288/}}, as well as between ''x'' {{IPA|/s/}} and ''s'' {{IPA|/\u0282/}}. However, these two pairs are becoming merged as {{IPA|/c/}} and {{IPA|/s/}} respectively.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Ph\u1ea1m|2008|p=35}}</ref>\n* In southern speech, the phoneme {{IPA|/r/}}, generally represented in Vietnamese linguistics by the letter {{angbr|r}}, has a number of variant pronunciations that depend on the speaker. More than one pronunciation may even be found within a single speaker. It may occur as a [[Voiced retroflex fricative|retroflex fricative]] {{IPA|[\u0290]}}, an [[alveolar approximant]] {{IPA|[\u0279]}}, a [[Alveolar tap|flap]] {{IPA|[\u027e]}} or a [[Alveolar trill|trill]] {{IPA|[r]}}.\n* Some rural speakers from Mekong Delta merge {{IPA|/r/}} and {{IPA|/\u0263/}} into {{IPA|/\u0263/}}, or {{IPA|/r/}} and /j/ into /j/, although this is not considered standard.\n\n===Comparison of initials===\nThe table below summarizes these sound correspondences:\n\n:{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[Diaphoneme]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Hanoi\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Saigon\n! colspan=\"3\" | Example\n|-\n! word\n! Hanoi\n! Saigon\n|-\n! {{IPA|/v/}}\n| {{IPA|/v/}}\n| {{IPA|/v/}} or {{IPA|/j/}}\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | ''v\u1ee3'' &nbsp; 'wife'\n| {{IPA|[v\u0259\u02e8\u02e9\u02c0]}}\n| {{IPA|[v\u0259\u02e8\u02e7]}} or {{IPA|[j\u0259\u02e8\u02e7]}}\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|/z/}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" | {{IPA|/z/}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|/j/}}\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | ''da'' &nbsp; 'skin'\n| rowspan=\"3\" | {{IPA|[za\u02e7]}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|[ja\u02e7]}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | ''gia'' &nbsp; 'to add'\n|-\n! {{IPA|/r/}}\n| {{IPA|/r/}}\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | ''ra'' &nbsp; 'to go out'\n| {{IPA|[ra\u02e7]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/c/}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|/c/}}\n| {{IPA|/c/}}\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | ''ch\u1ebb'' &nbsp; 'split'\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|[c\u025b\u02e7\u02e9]}}\n| {{IPA|[c\u025b\u02e9\u02e5]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/\u0288/}}\n| {{IPA|/c/}} or {{IPA|/\u0288/}}\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | ''tr\u1ebb'' &nbsp; 'young'\n| {{IPA|[c\u025b\u02e9\u02e5]}} or {{IPA|[\u0288\u025b\u02e9\u02e5]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/s/}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|/s/}}\n| {{IPA|/s/}}\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | ''xinh'' &nbsp; 'beautiful'\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|[si\u014b\u031f\u02e7]}}\n| {{IPA|[s\u0268n\u02e7]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/\u0282/}}\n| {{IPA|/s/}} or {{IPA|/\u0282/}}\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | ''sinh'' &nbsp; 'born'\n| {{IPA|[s\u0268n\u02e7]}} or {{IPA|[\u0282\u0268n\u02e7]}}\n|}\n\n==Vowels==\n\n===Vowel nuclei===\n[[File:Hanoi Vietnamese vowel chart.svg|thumb|upright=1.13|Vowel chart of Hanoi [[monophthong]]s according to {{Harvcoltxt|Kirby|2011|p=384}}]]\n[[File:Hanoi Vietnamese diphthong chart.svg|thumb|upright=1.13|Vowel chart of Hanoi [[diphthong]]s according to {{Harvcoltxt|Kirby|2011|p=384}}]]\n\n:{| class=\"wikitable nowrap\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!  \n! [[Front vowel|Front]]\n! [[Central vowel|Central]]\n! [[Back vowel|Back]]\n|- style=\"height: 65px\"\n! [[Centering diphthong|Centering]]\n| {{IPA|/i\u0259\u032f/}} {{angbr|ia~i\u00ea}}\n| {{IPA|/\u0268\u0259\u032f/}} {{angbr|\u01b0a~\u01b0\u01a1}}\n| {{IPA|/u\u0259\u032f/}} {{angbr|ua~u\u00f4}}\n|- style=\"height: 65px\"\n! [[Close vowel|Close]]\n| {{IPAslink|i}} {{angbr|i, y}}\n| {{IPAslink|\u0268}} {{angbr|\u01b0}}\n| {{IPAslink|u}} {{angbr|u}}\n|- style=\"height: 65px;\"\n! [[Close-mid vowel|Close-mid]]/<br>[[Mid vowel|Mid]]\n| {{IPAslink|e}} {{angbr|\u00ea}}\n| {{IPAslink|\u0259}} {{angbr|\u01a1}}\n<br>{{IPAslink|\u0259|\u0259\u0306}} {{angbr|\u00e2}}\n| {{IPAslink|o}} {{angbr|\u00f4}}\n|- style=\"height: 65px;\"\n! [[Open-mid vowel|Open-mid]]/<br>[[Open vowel|Open]]\n| {{IPAslink|\u025b}} {{angbr|e}}\n| {{IPAslink|\u00e4|a}} {{angbr|a}}\n<br>{{IPAslink|\u00e4|\u0103}} {{angbr|\u0103}}\n| {{IPAslink|\u0254}} {{angbr|o}}\n|}\n\nThe [[International Phonetic Alphabet|IPA]] chart of vowel nuclei above is based on the sounds in Hanoi Vietnamese; other regions may have different inventories. Vowel nuclei consist of [[monophthong]]s (simple [[vowel]]s) and three [[centering diphthong]]s.\n\n* All vowels are [[Roundedness|unrounded]] except for the four back rounded vowels: {{IPA|/u, o, \u0254, u\u0259\u032f/}}.\n* {{IPA|/\u0259\u0306/}} and {{IPA|/\u0103/}} are pronounced [[Vowel length|short]] \u2014 shorter than the other vowels.\n* While there are small consistent spectral differences between {{IPA|/\u0259\u0306/}} and {{IPA|/\u0259/}}, it has not been established that they are perceptually significant.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Kirby|2011|p=384}}</ref>\n* {{IPA|/\u0268/}}: Many descriptions, such as Thompson,<ref name=\"Harvcoltxt|Thompson|1965\"/> {{Harvcoltxt|Nguy\u1ec5n|1970}}, {{Harvcoltxt|Nguy\u1ec5n|1997}}, consider this vowel to be [[Close back unrounded vowel|close back unrounded]]: {{IPA|[\u026f]}}. However, Han's<ref name=\"Harvcoltxt|Han|1966\">{{Harvcoltxt|Han|1966}}</ref> instrumental analysis indicates that it is more central than back. {{Harvcoltxt|Hoang|1965}}, {{Harvcoltxt|Brunelle|2003}} and {{Harvcoltxt|Ph\u1ea1m|2006}} also transcribe this vowel as central.\n{{clear}}\n\n===Closing sequences===\nIn Vietnamese, vowel nuclei are able to combine with offglides {{IPA|/j/}} or {{IPA|/w/}} to form closing [[diphthong]]s and [[triphthong]]s. Below is a chart<ref>From {{Harvcoltxt|Nguy\u1ec5n|1997}}</ref> listing the closing sequences of general northern speech.\n\n:{| class=\"wikitable nowrap\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|/w/}} offglide\n! colspan=\"2\" | {{IPA|/j/}} offglide\n|-\n! [[Front vowel|Front]]\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Central vowel|Central]]\n! [[Back vowel|Back]]\n|-\n! [[Centering diphthong|Centering]]\n| {{IPA|/i\u0259\u032fw/}} {{angbr|i\u00eau}}\n| {{IPA|/\u0268\u0259\u032fw/}} {{angbr|\u01b0\u01a1u}}\n| {{IPA|/\u0268\u0259\u032fj/}} {{angbr|\u01b0\u01a1i}}\n| {{IPA|/u\u0259\u032fj/}} {{angbr|u\u00f4i}}\n|-\n! [[Close vowel|Close]]\n| {{IPA|/iw/}} {{angbr|iu}}\n| {{IPA|/\u0268w/}} {{angbr|\u01b0u}}\n| {{IPA|/\u0268j/}} {{angbr|\u01b0i}}\n| {{IPA|/uj/}} {{angbr|ui}}\n|-\n! [[Close-mid vowel|Close-mid]]/<br>[[Mid vowel|Mid]]\n| {{IPA|/ew/}} {{angbr|\u00eau}}\n| \u2013\n<br>{{IPA|/\u0259\u0306w/}} {{angbr|\u00e2u}}\n| {{IPA|/\u0259j/}} {{angbr|\u01a1i}}\n<br>{{IPA|/\u0259\u0306j/}} {{angbr|\u00e2y}}\n| {{IPA|/oj/}} {{angbr|\u00f4i}}\n|-\n! [[Open-mid vowel|Open-mid]]/<br>[[Open vowel|Open]]\n| {{IPA|/\u025bw/}} {{angbr|eo}}\n| {{IPA|/aw/}} {{angbr|ao}}\n<br>{{IPA|/\u0103w/}} {{angbr|au}}\n| {{IPA|/aj/}} {{angbr|ai}}\n<br>{{IPA|/\u0103j/}} {{angbr|ay}}\n| {{IPA|/\u0254j/}} {{angbr|oi}}\n|}\n\n{{Harvcoltxt|Thompson|1965}} says that in Hanoi, words spelled with ''\u01b0u'' and ''\u01b0\u01a1u'' are pronounced {{IPA|/iw, i\u0259w/}}, respectively, whereas other dialects in the Tonkin delta pronounce them as {{IPA|/\u0268w/}} and {{IPA|/\u0268\u0259w/}}. This observation is also made by {{Harvcoltxt|Ph\u1ea1m|2008}} and {{Harvcoltxt|Kirby|2011}}.\n\n==Final stops==\nWhen stops {{IPA|/p, t, k/}} occur at the end of words, they have [[no audible release]] ({{IPA|[p\u031a, t\u031a, k\u031a]}}):\n\n:{| cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"line-height: 1.0em;\"\n| ''\u0111\u00e1p''\n| 'to reply'\n| {{IPA|/\u0257ap/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0257ap\u031a]}}\n|-\n| ''m\u00e1t''\n| 'cool'\n| {{IPA|/mat/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[mat\u031a]}}\n|-\n| ''kh\u00e1c''\n| 'different'\n| {{IPA|/xak/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[xak\u031a]}}\n|}\n\nWhen the velar consonants {{IPA|/k, \u014b/}} are after {{IPA|/u, o, \u0254/}}, they are articulated with a simultaneous bilabial closure {{IPA|[k\u0361p\u031a, \u014b\u0361m]}} (i.e. [[doubly articulated]]) or are strongly [[labialization|labialized]] {{IPA|[k\u031a\u02b7, \u014b\u02b7]}}.\n\n:{| cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"line-height: 1.0em;\"\n| ''\u0111\u1ee5c''\n| 'muddy'\n| {{IPA|/\u0257uk/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0257uk\u0361p\u031a]}}, {{IPA|[\u0257uk\u031a\u02b7]}}\n|-\n| ''\u0111\u1ed9c''\n| 'poison'\n| {{IPA|/\u0257ok/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0257\u0259\u0306wk\u0361p\u031a]}}, {{IPA|[\u0257\u0259\u0306wk\u031a\u02b7]}}\n|-\n| ''\u0111\u1ecdc''\n| 'to read'\n| {{IPA|/\u0257\u0254k/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0257\u0103wk\u0361p\u031a]}}, {{IPA|[\u0257\u0103wk\u031a\u02b7]}}\n|-\n| ''ung''\n| 'cancer'\n| {{IPA|/u\u014b/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[u\u014b\u0361m]}}, {{IPA|[u\u014b\u02b7]}}\n|-\n| ''\u00f4ng''\n| 'man'\n| {{IPA|/o\u014b/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0259\u0306w\u014b\u0361m]}}, {{IPA|[\u0259\u0306w\u014b\u02b7]}}\n|-\n| ''ong''\n| 'bee'\n| {{IPA|/\u0254\u014b/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0103w\u014b\u0361m]}}, {{IPA|[\u0103w\u014b\u02b7]}}\n|}\n\n===Hanoi finals===\n====Analysis of final ''ch'', ''nh''====\n\nThe pronunciation of syllable-final ''ch'' and ''nh'' in Hanoi Vietnamese has had different analyses. One analysis, that of {{Harvcoltxt|Thompson|1965}} has them as being phonemes {{IPA|/c, \u0272/}}, where {{IPA|/c/}} contrasts with both syllable-final ''t'' {{IPA|/t/}} and ''c'' {{IPA|/k/}} and {{IPA|/\u0272/}} contrasts with syllable-final ''n'' {{IPA|/n/}} and ''ng'' {{IPA|/\u014b/}}. Final {{IPA|/c, \u0272/}} is, then, identified with syllable-initial {{IPA|/c, \u0272/}}.\n\nAnother analysis has final {{angbr|ch}} and {{angbr|nh}} as representing predictable [[allophonic]] variants of the velar phonemes {{IPA|/k/}} and {{IPA|/\u014b/}} that occur after upper front vowels {{IPA|/i/}} (orthographic {{angbr|i}}) and {{IPA|/e/}} (orthographic {{angbr|\u00ea}}). This analysis interprets orthographic \u27e8ach\u27e9 and \u27e8anh\u27e9 as an underlying {{IPA|/\u025b/}}, which becomes phonetically open and diphthongized: {{IPA|/\u025bk/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u0103jk\u031f\u031a]}}, {{IPA|/\u025b\u014b/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u0103j\u014b\u031f]}}.<ref>Although there are some words where orthographic {{angbr|c}} and {{angbr|ng}} occur after {{IPA|/\u025b/}}, these words are few and are mostly loanwords or [[onomatopoeia]]</ref> This diphthongization also affects \u27e8\u00each\u27e9 and \u27e8\u00eanh\u27e9: {{IPA|/ek/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u0259\u0306jk\u031f\u031a]}}, {{IPA|/e\u014b/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[\u0259\u0306j\u014b\u031f]}}.\n\nArguments for the second analysis include the limited distribution of final {{IPA|[c]}} and {{IPA|[\u0272]}}, the gap in the distribution of {{IPA|[k]}} and {{IPA|[\u014b]}} which do not occur after {{IPA|[i]}} and {{IPA|[e]}}, the pronunciation of \u27e8ach\u27e9 and \u27e8anh\u27e9 as {{IPA|[\u025bc]}} and {{IPA|[\u025b\u0272]}} in certain conservative central dialects,<ref name=\"rhyme\"/> and the patterning of {{IPA|[k]}}~{{IPA|[c]}} and {{IPA|[\u014b]}}~{{IPA|[\u0272]}} in certain reduplicated words. Additionally, final {{IPA|[c]}} is not articulated as far forward as the initial {{IPA|[c]}}: {{IPA|[c]}} and {{IPA|[\u0272]}} are pre-velar {{IPA|[k\u031f, \u014b\u031f]}} with no alveolar contact.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Kirby|2011|p=383}}</ref>\n\nThe first analysis closely follows the surface pronunciation of a slightly different Hanoi dialect than the second. In this dialect, the {{IPA|/a/}} in {{IPA|/ac/}} and {{IPA|/a\u0272/}} is not diphthongized but is actually articulated more forward, approaching a front vowel {{IPA|[\u00e6]}}. This results in a three-way contrast between the rimes ''\u0103n'' {{IPA|[\u00e6\u0308n]}} vs. ''anh'' {{IPA|[\u00e6\u0308\u0272]}} vs. ''\u0103ng'' {{IPA|[\u00e6\u0308\u014b]}}. For this reason, a separate phonemic {{IPA|/\u0272/}} is posited.\n\n====Table of Hanoi finals====\nThe following [[syllable rime|rime]]s ending with [[velar consonant]]s have been [[diphthong]]ized in the Hanoi dialect:<ref name=\"rhyme\">{{Harvcoltxt|Ph\u1ea1m|2006}}</ref>\n\n:{| cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"line-height: 1.0em;\"\n| ''ong'', ''oc''\n| {{IPA|/\u0254\u014b/}}, {{IPA|/\u0254k/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0103w\u014b\u0361m]}}, {{IPA|[\u0103wk\u0361p\u031a]}}\n|-\n| ''\u00f4ng'', ''\u00f4c''\n| {{IPA|/o\u014b/}}, {{IPA|/ok/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0259\u0306w\u014b\u0361m]}}, {{IPA|[\u0259\u0306wk\u0361p\u031a]}}\n|-\n| ''anh'', ''ach''\n| {{IPA|/\u025b\u014b/}}, {{IPA|/\u025bk/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0103j\u014b\u031f]}}, {{IPA|[\u0103jk\u031f\u031a]}}\n|-\n| ''\u00eanh'', ''\u00each''\n| {{IPA|/e\u014b/}}, {{IPA|/ek/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0259\u0306j\u014b\u031f]}}, {{IPA|[\u0259\u0306jk\u031f\u031a]}}\n|}\n\nWith the above phonemic analyses, the following is a table of rimes ending in {{IPA|/n, t, \u014b, k/}} in the Hanoi dialect:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n! {{IPA|/\u0103/}}\n! {{IPA|/a/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u025b/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u0254/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u0259\u0306/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u0259/}}\n! {{IPA|/e/}}\n! {{IPA|/o/}}\n! {{IPA|/i/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u0268/}}\n! {{IPA|/u/}}\n! {{IPA|/i\u0259\u032f/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u0268\u0259\u032f/}}\n! {{IPA|/u\u0259\u032f/}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/n/}}\n| ''\u0103n''\n| ''an''\n| ''en''\n| ''on''\n| ''\u00e2n''\n| ''\u01a1n''\n| ''\u00ean''\n| ''\u00f4n''\n| ''in''\n| ''\u01b0n''\n| ''un''\n| ''i\u00ean''\n| ''\u01b0\u01a1n''\n| ''u\u00f4n''\n|-\n! {{IPA|/t/}}\n| ''\u0103t''\n| ''at''\n| ''et''\n| ''ot''\n| ''\u00e2t''\n| ''\u01a1t''\n| ''\u00eat''\n| ''\u00f4t''\n| ''it''\n| ''\u01b0t''\n| ''ut''\n| ''i\u00eat''\n| ''\u01b0\u01a1t''\n| ''u\u00f4t''\n|-\n! {{IPA|/\u014b/}}\n| ''\u0103ng''\n| ''ang''\n| ''anh''\n| ''ong''\n| ''\u00e2ng''\n| \u2013\n| ''\u00eanh''\n| ''\u00f4ng''\n| ''inh''\n| ''\u01b0ng''\n| ''ung''\n| ''i\u00eang''\n| ''\u01b0\u01a1ng''\n| ''u\u00f4ng''\n|-\n! {{IPA|/k/}}\n| ''\u0103c''\n| ''ac''\n| ''ach''\n| ''oc''\n| ''\u00e2c''\n| \u2013\n| ''\u00each''\n| ''\u00f4c''\n| ''ich''\n| ''\u01b0c''\n| ''uc''\n| ''i\u00eac''\n| ''\u01b0\u01a1c''\n| ''u\u00f4c''\n|}\n\n===Saigon finals===\n====Merger of finals====\nWhile the variety of Vietnamese spoken in Hanoi has preserved finals faithfully from Middle Vietnamese, the variety spoken in Saigon has drastically changed its finals. Rimes ending in {{IPA|/k, \u014b/}} and {{IPA|/t, n/}} were merged except after {{IPA|/\u025b, \u0254/}}; in these rimes, {{IPA|/k, \u014b/}} is the underlying phoneme while {{IPA|[k\u0361p, \u014b\u0361m]}} occurs after rounded vowels {{IPA|/u, o/}} and {{IPA|[t, n]}} occurs after front vowels {{IPA|/i, e/}}.<ref name=\"rhyme\"/> Subsequently, vowels in labial-velar rimes became diphthongized while vowels in alveolar rimes became centralized<ref>{{citation | author=Ph\u1ea1m, Andrea H\u00f2a | year=2013 | title=Synchronic evidence for historical hypothesis \u2013 Vietnamese palatals | journal=Linguistic Association of Canada and the United States Forum |volume=39 |url= https://www.researchgate.net/publication/278035542}}</ref>in a similar fashion to the Hanoi dialect.\n\n====Table of Saigon finals====\nThe following [[syllable rime|rime]]s have been [[diphthong]]ized or [[relative_articulation#Centralized_vowels|centralized]] in the Saigon dialect:<ref name=\"rhyme\"/>\n:{| cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"line-height: 1.0em;\"\n| ''ong'', ''oc''\n| {{IPA|/\u0254\u014b\u0361m/}}, {{IPA|/\u0254k\u0361p/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0103w\u014b\u0361m]}}, {{IPA|[\u0103wk\u0361p\u031a]}}\n|-\n| ''\u00f4ng'', ''\u00f4c''\n| {{IPA|/o\u014b\u0361m/}}, {{IPA|/ok\u0361p/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0259\u0306w\u014b\u0361m]}}, {{IPA|[\u0259\u0306wk\u0361p\u031a]}}\n|-\n| ''anh'', ''ach''\n| {{IPA|/\u025bn/}}, {{IPA|/\u025bt/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0103n]}}, {{IPA|[\u0103t\u031a]}}\n|-\n| ''\u00ean'', ''\u00eat''\n| {{IPA|/en/}}, {{IPA|/et/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0259\u0306n]}}, {{IPA|[\u0259\u0306t\u031a]}}\n|-\n| ''in'', ''it''\n| {{IPA|/in/}}, {{IPA|/it/}}\n| \u2192\n| {{IPA|[\u0268n]}}, {{IPA|[\u0268t\u031a]}}\n|}\n\nThe ''\u00f4ng'', ''\u1ed1c'' rimes is merged into ''ong'', ''\u00f3c'' as {{IPA|[\u0103w\u014b\u0361m]}}, {{IPA|[\u0103wk\u0361p\u031a]}} but not with ''\u00f4n'', ''\u1ed1t'' as pronounced {{IPA|[o\u014b\u0361m]}}, {{IPA|[ok\u0361p\u031a]}}.\n\nWith the above phonemic analyses, the following is a table of rimes ending in {{IPA|/n, t, \u014b, k, \u014b\u0361m, k\u0361p/}} in the Saigon dialect:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!\n!{{IPA|/\u0103/}}\n!{{IPA|/a/}}\n!{{IPA|/\u025b/}}\n!{{IPA|/\u0254/}}\n!{{IPA|/\u0259\u0306/}}\n!{{IPA|/\u0259/}}\n!{{IPA|/e/}}\n!{{IPA|/o/}}\n!{{IPA|/i/}}\n!{{IPA|/\u0268/}}\n!{{IPA|/u/}}\n!{{IPA|/i\u0259\u032f/}}\n!{{IPA|/\u0268\u0259\u032f/}}\n!{{IPA|/u\u0259\u032f/}}\n|-\n!{{IPA|/n/}}\n|\n|\n| \u2013<br />'''''anh'''''\n|\n|\n|\n|''\u00ean''<br />'''''\u00eanh'''''\n|\n|''in''<br />'''''inh'''''\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!{{IPA|/t/}}\n|\n|\n| \u2013<br />'''''ach'''''\n|\n|\n|\n|''\u00eat''<br />'''''\u00each'''''\n|\n|''it''<br />'''''ich'''''\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!{{IPA|/\u014b/}}\n|'''''\u0103n'''''<br />''\u0103ng''\n|'''''an'''''<br />''ang''\n|'''''en'''''<br />\u2013\n|'''''on'''''<br />\u2013\n|'''''\u00e2n'''''<br />''\u00e2ng''\n|'''''\u01a1n'''''<br />\u2013\n|\n|\n|\n|'''''\u01b0n'''''<br />''\u01b0ng''\n|\n|'''''i\u00ean'''''<br />''i\u00eang''\n|'''''\u01b0\u01a1n'''''<br />''\u01b0\u01a1ng''\n|'''''u\u00f4n'''''<br />''u\u00f4ng''\n|-\n!{{IPA|/k/}}\n|'''''\u0103t'''''<br />''\u0103c''\n|'''''at'''''<br />''ac''\n|'''''et'''''<br />\u2013\n|'''''ot'''''<br />\u2013\n|'''''\u00e2t'''''<br />''\u00e2c''\n|'''''\u01a1t'''''<br />\u2013\n|\n|\n|\n|'''''\u01b0t'''''<br />''\u01b0c''\n|\n|'''''i\u00eat'''''<br />''i\u00eac''\n|'''''\u01b0\u01a1t'''''<br />''\u01b0\u01a1c''\n|'''''u\u00f4t'''''<br />''u\u00f4c''\n|-\n!{{IPA|/\u014b\u0361m/}}\n|\n|\n|\n| \u2013<br />''ong / '''\u00f4ng'''''\n|\n|\n|\n|'''''\u00f4n'''''<br />\u2013\n|\n|\n|'''''un'''''<br />''ung''\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!{{IPA|/k\u0361p/}}\n|\n|\n|\n| \u2013<br />''oc / '''\u00f4c'''''\n|\n|\n|\n|'''''\u00f4t'''''<br />\u2013\n|\n|\n|'''''ut'''''<br />''uc''\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! colspan=\"15\" |Combinations that have changed their pronunciation due to merger are bolded.\n|}\n\n==Tone==\nVietnamese vowels are all pronounced with an inherent [[Tone (linguistics)|tone]]. Tones differ in\n\n* pitch\n* length\n* contour melody\n* intensity\n* [[phonation]] (with or without accompanying constricted vocal cords)\n\nUnlike many Native American, African, and Chinese languages, Vietnamese tones do not rely solely on [[pitch contour]]. Vietnamese often uses instead a [[register complex]] (which is a combination of phonation type, pitch, length, vowel quality, etc.). So perhaps a better description would be that Vietnamese is a register language and not a \"pure\" tonal language.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Ph\u1ea1m|2003|p=93}}</ref>\n\nIn Vietnamese orthography, tone is indicated by diacritics written above or below the vowel.\n\n===Six-tone analysis===\n\nThere is much variation among speakers concerning how tone is realized phonetically. There are differences between varieties of Vietnamese spoken in the major geographic areas (northern, central, southern) and smaller differences within the major areas (e.g. Hanoi vs. other northern varieties). In addition, there seems to be variation among individuals. More research is needed to determine the remaining details of tone realization and the variation among speakers.\n\n====Northern varieties====\n\nThe six tones in the Hanoi and other northern varieties are:\n\n:{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n! [[Tone name]]\n! Tone ID\n! Description\n! Chao Tone Contour\n! Diacritic\n! Example\n|-\n| ''ngang'' \"level\"\n| A1\n| mid level\n| {{IPA|\u02e7}} (33)\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | (no mark)\n| ''ba'' ('three')\n|-\n| ''huy\u1ec1n'' \"deep\"\n| A2\n| low falling (breathy)\n| {{IPA|\u02e8\u02e9}} (21) or (31)\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''`'''\n| ''b\u00e0'' ('lady')\n|-\n| ''s\u1eafc'' \"sharp\"\n| B1\n| mid rising, tense\n| {{IPA|\u02e7\u02e5}} (35)\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''\u00b4'''\n| ''b\u00e1'' ('governor')\n|-\n| ''n\u1eb7ng'' \"heavy\"\n| B2\n| mid falling, glottalized, short\n| {{IPA|\u02e7\u02c0\u02e8\u0294}} (3\u02c02\u0294)<small> or </small>{{IPA|\u02e7\u02c0\u02e9\u0294}} (3\u02c01\u0294)\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''&nbsp;\u0323'''\n| ''b\u1ea1'' ('at random')\n|-\n| ''h\u1ecfi'' \"asking\"\n| C1\n| mid falling(-rising), harsh\n| {{IPA|\u02e7\u02e9\u02e7}} (313) or (323) or (31)\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''&nbsp;\u0309'''\n| ''b\u1ea3'' ('poison')\n|-\n| ''ng\u00e3'' \"tumbling\"\n| C2\n| mid rising, glottalized\n| {{IPA|\u02e7\u02c0\u02e5}} (3\u02c05) or (4\u02c05)\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''\u02dc'''\n| ''b\u00e3'' ('residue')\n|}\n\n[[File:VietnameseToneNorthern.png|thumb|upright=1.93|Northern Vietnamese (non-Hanoi) tones as uttered by a male speaker in isolation. From {{Harvcoltxt|Nguy\u1ec5n|Edmondson|1998}}]]\n[[File:VietnameseToneHanoi.png|thumb|upright=1.93|Hanoi tones as uttered by a female speaker in isolation. From {{Harvcoltxt|Nguy\u1ec5n|Edmondson|1998}}]]\n[[File:VietnameseToneHanoi2.png|thumb|upright=1.93|Hanoi tones as uttered by a different female speaker in isolation. From {{Harvcoltxt|Nguy\u1ec5n|Edmondson|1998}}]]\n\n'''Ngang tone:'''\n\n*The ''ngang'' tone is level at around the mid level (33) and is produced with [[modal voice]] [[phonation]] (i.e. with \"normal\" phonation). Alexandre de Rhodes (1651) describes this as \"level\"; {{Harvcoltxt|Nguy\u1ec5n|1997}} describes it as \"high (or mid) level\".\n\n'''Huy\u1ec1n tone:'''\n\n*The ''huy\u1ec1n'' tone starts low-mid and falls (21). Some Hanoi speakers start at a somewhat higher point (31). It is sometimes accompanied by [[breathy voice]] (or lax) phonation in some speakers, but this is lacking in other speakers: ''b\u00e0'' = {{IPA|[\u0253a\u02e8\u02e9]}}.<ref>For example, {{Harvcoltxt|Nguy\u1ec5n|Edmondson|1998}} show a male speaker from [[Nam \u0110\u1ecbnh Province|Nam \u0110\u1ecbnh]] with [[lax voice]] and a female speaker from Hanoi with breathy voice for the ''huy\u1ec1n'' tone while another male speaker from Hanoi has modal voice for the ''huy\u1ec1n''.</ref> Alexandre de Rhodes (1651) describes this as \"grave-lowering\"; {{Harvcoltxt|Nguy\u1ec5n|1997}} describes it as \"low falling\".\n\n'''H\u1ecfi tone:'''\n\n* The ''h\u1ecfi'' tone starts a mid level and falls. It starts with modal voice phonation, which moves increasingly toward [[tense voice]] with accompanying [[harsh voice]] (although the harsh voice seems to vary according to speaker). In Hanoi, the tone is mid falling (31). In other northern speakers, the tone is mid falling and then rises back to the mid level (313 or 323). This characteristic gives this tone its traditional description as \"dipping\". However, the falling-rising contour is most obvious in citation forms or when syllable-final; in other positions and when in fast speech, the rising contour is negligible. The ''h\u1ecfi'' also is relatively short compared with the other tones, but not as short as the ''n\u1eb7ng'' tone. Alexandre de Rhodes (1651) describes this as \"smooth-rising\"; {{Harvcoltxt|Nguy\u1ec5n|1997}} describes it as \"dipping-rising\".\n\n'''Ng\u00e3 tone:'''\n\n* The ''ng\u00e3'' tone is mid rising (35). Many speakers begin the vowel with modal voice, followed by strong [[creaky voice]] starting toward the middle of the vowel, which is then lessening as the end of the syllable is approached. Some speakers with more dramatic glottalization have a [[glottal stop]] closure in the middle of the vowel (i.e. as {{IPA|[V\u0294V]}}). In Hanoi Vietnamese, the tone starts at a higher pitch (45) than other northern speakers. Alexandre de Rhodes (1651) describes this as \"chesty-raised\"; {{Harvcoltxt|Nguy\u1ec5n|1997}} describes it as \"creaking-rising\".\n\n'''S\u1eafc tone:'''\n\n*The ''s\u1eafc'' tone starts as mid and then rises (35) in much the same way as the ''ng\u00e3'' tone. It is accompanied by [[tense voice]] phonation throughout the duration of the vowel. In some Hanoi speakers, the ''ng\u00e3'' tone is noticeably higher than the ''s\u1eafc'' tone, for example: ''s\u1eafc'' = {{IPA|\u02e7\u02e6}} (34); ''ng\u00e3'' = {{IPA|\u02e6\u02c0\u02e5}} (45). Alexandre de Rhodes (1651) describes this as \"acute-angry\"; {{Harvcoltxt|Nguy\u1ec5n|1997}} describes it as \"high (or mid) rising\".\n\n'''N\u1eb7ng tone:'''\n\n* The ''n\u1eb7ng'' tone starts mid or low-mid and rapidly falls in pitch (32 or 21). It starts with tense voice that becomes increasingly tense until the vowel ends in a glottal stop closure. This tone is noticeably shorter than the other tones. Alexandre de Rhodes (1651) describes this as \"chesty-heavy\"; {{Harvcoltxt|Nguy\u1ec5n|1997}} describes it as \"constricted\".\n\n====Southern varieties====\n{{Expand section|date=January 2011}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n![[Tone name]]\n! Tone ID\n! Description\n! Chao Tone Contour\n! Diacritic\n! Example\n|-\n|''ngang'' \"level\"\n| A1\n| mid flat level\n|{{IPA|\u02e7}} (33)\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | (no mark)\n|''ba'' ('three')\n|-\n|''huy\u1ec1n'' \"deep\"\n| A2\n| low falling\n|{{IPA|\u02e8\u02e9}} (21)\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |'''`'''\n|''b\u00e0'' ('lady')\n|-\n|''s\u1eafc'' \"sharp\"\n| B1\n| high rising\n|{{IPA|\u02e7\u02e5}} (35)\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |'''\u00b4'''\n|''b\u00e1'' ('governor')\n|-\n|''n\u1eb7ng'' \"heavy\"\n| B2\n| low falling-rising\n| \u02e8\u02e9\u02e8 (212)\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |'''&nbsp;\u0323'''\n|''b\u1ea1'' ('at random')\n|-\n|''h\u1ecfi'' \"asking\"\n| C1\n| rowspan=\"2\" | mid falling-rising\n| \u02e8\u02e9\u02e6 (214)\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |'''&nbsp;\u0309'''\n|''b\u1ea3'' ('poison')\n|-\n|''ng\u00e3'' \"tumbling\"\n| C2\n| \u02e8\u02e9\u02e6 (214)\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" |'''\u02dc'''\n|''b\u00e3'' ('residue')\n|}\nThe Southern tones contour of ''ngang'', ''s\u1eafc'', ''huy\u1ec1n'' is similar as Northern tones, however, these tones are produced with normal voice instead of breathy voice.\n\nThe ''n\u1eb7ng'' tone are pronounced as low rising tone (12) [\u02e9\u02e8] in fast speech or low falling-rising tone (212) [\u02e8\u02e9\u02e8] in more careful utterance. \n\nThe ''ng\u00e3'' and ''h\u1ecfi'' tone are merged into a mid falling-rising (214) [\u02e8\u02e9\u02e6] which is somewhat similar ''h\u1ecfi'' tone of non-Hanoi Northern accent mentioned above.\n[[File:Southern_Vietnamese_tone_system_(Speaker_10).png|alt=|thumb|Southern Vietnamese tone system from female native speaker. From Jessica Bauman ''et al''. (2009)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Baumann|first=Jessica|last2=Blodgett|first2=Allison|last3=Rytting|first3=C. Anton|last4=Shamoo|first4=Jessica|date=|title=The ups and downs of Vietnamese tones|url=|journal=UNIVERSITY OF MARYLAND CENTER FOR ADVANCED STUDY OF LANGUAGE|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>]]\n\n====North-central and Central varieties====\n\n{{Expand section|date=May 2008}}\n\nNorth-central and Central Vietnamese varieties are fairly similar with respect to tone although within the North-central dialect region there is considerable internal variation.\n\nIt is sometimes said (by people from other provinces) that people from [[Ngh\u1ec7 An]] pronounce every tone as a n\u1eb7ng tone.\n\n===Eight-tone analysis===\n\nAn older analysis assumes eight tones rather than six.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Ph\u1ea1m|2003|p=45}}</ref>  This follows the lead of traditional Chinese phonology.  In [[Middle Chinese]], syllables ending in a vowel or nasal allowed for three tonal distinctions, but syllables ending with {{IPA|/p/}}, {{IPA|/t/}} or {{IPA|/k/}} had no tonal distinctions.  Rather, they were consistently pronounced with a short high tone, which was called the [[entering tone]] and considered a fourth tone. Similar considerations lead to the identification of two additional tones in Vietnamese for syllables ending in {{IPA|/p/}}, {{IPA|/t/}}, {{IPA|/c/}} and {{IPA|/k/}}.  These are not [[phoneme|phonemically]] distinct from the ''s\u1eafc'' and ''n\u1eb7ng'' tones, however, and hence not considered as separate tones by modern linguists and are not distinguished in the orthography.\n\n==Syllables and phonotactics==\nAccording to {{Harvcoltxt|Hannas|1997}}, there are 4,500 to 4,800 possible spoken syllables (depending on dialect), and the standard national orthography (''[[Qu\u1ed1c Ng\u1eef]]'') can represent 6,200 syllables (''Qu\u1ed1c Ng\u1eef'' orthography represents more phonemic distinctions than are made by any one dialect).<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Hannas|1997|p=88}}</ref> A description of syllable structure and exploration of its patterning according to the Prosodic Analysis approach of J.R. Firth is given in Henderson (1966).<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Henderson|1966}}</ref>\n\nThe Vietnamese [[syllable|syllable structure]] follows the scheme:\n\n:(C<sub>1</sub>)(w)V(G|C<sub>2</sub>)+T\n\nwhere\n:{| cellpadding=\"7\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"background: #f9f9f9;\"\n| style=\"vertical-align: top;\" |\n* C<sub>1</sub> = initial consonant onset\n* w = labiovelar on-glide {{IPA|/w/}}\n* V = vowel nucleus\n| style=\"vertical-align: top;\" |\n* G = off-glide coda ({{IPA|/j/}} or {{IPA|/w/}})\n* C<sub>2</sub> = final consonant coda\n* T = tone.\n|}\n\nIn other words, a syllable has an obligatory nucleus and tone, and can have an optional consonant [[syllable onset|onset]], an optional on-glide {{IPA|/w/}}, and an optional [[syllable coda|coda]] or off-glide.\n\nMore explicitly, the syllable types are as follows:\n\n:{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"font-size: 85%; background: #f2f2f2;\"\n! Syllable\n! Example\n! Syllable\n! Example\n|-\n| V\n| \u00ea \"eh\"\n| wV\n| u\u1ec3 \"sluggish\"\n|-\n| VC\n| \u00e1m \"possess (by ghosts,.etc)\"\n| wVC\n| o\u00e1n \"bear a grudge\"\n|-\n| VC\n| \u1edbt \"capsicum\"\n| wVC\n| o\u1eaft \"little imp\"\n|-\n| CV\n| n\u1eef \"female\"\n| CwV\n| hu\u1ef7 \"cancel\"\n|-\n| CVC\n| c\u01a1m \"rice\"\n| CwVC\n| to\u00e1n \"math\"\n|-\n| CVC\n| t\u1ee9c \"angry\"\n| CwVC\n| ho\u1eb7c \"or\"\n|}\n\n'''C<sub>1</sub>:''' Any consonant may occur in as an onset with the following exceptions:\n* {{IPA|/p/}} does not occur in native Vietnamese words\n\n'''w:''' the onglide {{IPA|/w/}} (sometimes transcribed instead as [[labialization]] {{IPA|[\u02b7]}} on a preceding consonant):\n\n* does not occur after labial consonants {{IPA|/\u0253, f, v, m/}}\n* does not occur after {{IPA|/n/}} in native Vietnamese words (it occurs in uncommon [[Sino-Vietnamese vocabulary|Sino-Vietnamese]] borrowings)\n\n'''V:''' The vowel nucleus V may be any of the following 14 monophthongs or diphthongs: {{IPA|/i, \u0268, u, e, \u0259, o, \u025b, \u0259\u0306, \u0254, \u0103, a, i\u0259\u032f, \u0268\u0259\u032f, u\u0259\u032f/}}.\n\n'''G:''' The offglide may be {{IPA|/j/}} or {{IPA|/w/}}. Together, V and G must form one of the diphthongs or triphthongs listed in the section on Vowels.\n* offglide {{IPA|/j/}} does not follow the front vowels {{IPA|/i, e, \u025b, i\u0259\u032f/}}\n* offglide {{IPA|/w/}} does not follow the rounded vowels {{IPA|/u, o, \u0254, u\u0259\u032f/}}\n* with some exceptions (such as ''[[wikt:khu\u1ef7u tay#Vietnamese|khu\u1ef7u tay]]'' \"elbow\"), the offglide {{IPA|/w/}} cannot occur if the syllable contains a {{IPA|/w/}} onglide\n\n'''C<sub>2</sub>:''' The optional coda C<sub>2</sub> is restricted to labial, coronal, and velar stops and nasals {{IPA|/p, t, k, m, n, \u014b/}}, which cannot cooccur with the offglides {{IPA|/j, w/}}.\n\n'''T:''' Syllables are spoken with an inherent [[tone (linguistics)|tone contour]]:\n* Six tone contours are possible for syllables with offglides {{IPA|/j, w/}}, closed syllables with nasal codas {{IPA|/m, n, \u014b/}}, and [[open syllable]]s\u2014i.e., those without consonant codas {{IPA|/p, t, k/}}.\n* If the syllable is closed with one of the oral stops {{IPA|/p, t, k/}}, only two contours are possible: the ''s\u1eafc'' and the ''n\u1eb7ng'' tones.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size: 90%\"\n|+ Common Vietnamese rimes {{ref|Notes|[Notes]}}\n! rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"2\" |\n! Zero coda\n! colspan=\"2\" | Off-glide coda\n! colspan=\"3\" | Nasal consonant coda\n! colspan=\"3\" | Stop consonant coda\n|-\n! {{IPA|\u2205}} || {{IPA|/j/}} || {{IPA|/w/}} || {{IPA|/m/}} || {{IPA|/n/}} || {{IPA|/\u014b/}} || {{IPA|/p/}} || {{IPA|/t/}} || {{IPA|/k/}}\n|-\n! rowspan=\"14\" style=\"width: 5px;\" | Vowel nucleus\n! {{IPA|/\u0103/}}\n| || ''\u1ea1y''<br>{{IPA|[\u0103j]}} || ''\u1ea1u''<br>{{IPA|[\u0103w]}} || ''\u1eb7m''<br>{{IPA|[\u0103m]}} || ''\u1eb7n''<br>{{IPA|[\u0103n]}} || ''\u1eb7ng''<br>{{IPA|[\u0103\u014b]}} || ''\u1eb7p''<br>{{IPA|[\u0103p]}} || ''\u1eb7t''<br>{{IPA|[\u0103t]}} || ''\u1eb7c''<br>{{IPA|[\u0103k]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/a/}}\n| ''\u1ea1'', ''(gi)\u00e0'', ''(gi)\u1ea3'', ''(gi)\u00e3'', ''(gi)\u00e1''<br>{{IPA|[a]}} || ''\u1ea1i''<br>{{IPA|[aj]}} || ''\u1ea1o''<br>{{IPA|[aw]}} || ''\u1ea1m''<br>{{IPA|[am]}} || ''\u1ea1n''<br>{{IPA|[an]}} || ''\u1ea1ng''<br>{{IPA|[a\u014b]}} || ''\u1ea1p''<br>{{IPA|[ap]}} || ''\u1ea1t''<br>{{IPA|[at]}} || ''\u1ea1c''<br>{{IPA|[ak]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/\u025b/}}\n| ''\u1eb9''<br>{{IPA|[\u025b]}} || || ''\u1eb9o''<br>{{IPA|[\u025bw]}} || ''\u1eb9m''<br>{{IPA|[\u025bm]}} || ''\u1eb9n''<br>{{IPA|[\u025bn]}} || ''\u1ea1nh''<br>{{IPA|[\u0103j\u014b]}} || ''\u1eb9p''<br>{{IPA|[\u025bp]}} || ''\u1eb9t''<br>{{IPA|[\u025bt]}} || ''\u1ea1ch''<br>{{IPA|[\u0103jk]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/\u0254/}}\n| ''\u1ecd''<br>{{IPA|[\u0254]}} || ''\u1ecdi''<br>{{IPA|[\u0254j]}} || || ''\u1ecdm''<br>{{IPA|[\u0254m]}} || ''\u1ecdn''<br>{{IPA|[\u0254n]}} || ''\u1ecdng''<br>{{IPA|[\u0103w\u014b]}} || ''\u1ecdp''<br>{{IPA|[\u0254p]}} || ''\u1ecdt''<br>{{IPA|[\u0254t]}} || ''\u1ecdc''<br>{{IPA|[\u0103wk]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/\u0259\u0306/}}\n| || ''\u1eady''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259\u0306j]}} || ''\u1eadu''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259\u0306w]}} || ''\u1eadm''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259\u0306m]}} || ''\u1eadn''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259\u0306n]}} || ''\u1eadng''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259\u0306\u014b]}} || ''\u1eadp''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259\u0306p]}} || ''\u1eadt''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259\u0306t]}} || ''\u1eadc''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259\u0306k]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/\u0259/}}\n| ''\u1ee3''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259]}} || ''\u1ee3i''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259j]}} || || ''\u1ee3m''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259m]}} || ''\u1ee3n''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259n]}} || || ''\u1ee3p''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259p]}} || ''\u1ee3t''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259t]}} ||\n|-\n! {{IPA|/e/}}\n| ''\u1ec7''<br>{{IPA|[e]}} || || ''\u1ec7u''<br>{{IPA|[ew]}} || ''\u1ec7m''<br>{{IPA|[em]}} || ''\u1ec7n''<br>{{IPA|[en]}} || ''\u1ec7nh''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259\u0306j\u014b]}} || ''\u1ec7p''<br>{{IPA|[ep]}} || ''\u1ec7t''<br>{{IPA|[et]}} || ''\u1ec7ch''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259\u0306jk]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/o/}}\n| ''\u1ed9''<br>{{IPA|[o]}} || ''\u1ed9i''<br>{{IPA|[oj]}} || || ''\u1ed9m''<br>{{IPA|[om]}} || ''\u1ed9n''<br>{{IPA|[on]}} || ''\u1ed9ng''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259\u0306w\u014b]}} || ''\u1ed9p''<br>{{IPA|[op]}} || ''\u1ed9t''<br>{{IPA|[ot]}} || ''\u1ed9c''<br>{{IPA|[\u0259\u0306wk]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/i/}}\n| ''\u1ecb'', ''\u1ef5''<br>{{IPA|[i]}} || || ''\u1ecbu''<br>{{IPA|[iw]}} || ''\u1ecbm'', ''\u1ef5m''<br>{{IPA|[im]}} || ''\u1ecbn''<br>{{IPA|[in]}} || ''\u1ecbnh''<br>{{IPA|[i\u014b]}} || ''\u1ecbp'', ''\u1ef5p''<br>{{IPA|[ip]}} || ''\u1ecbt''<br>{{IPA|[it]}} || ''\u1ecbch'', ''\u1ef5ch''<br>{{IPA|[ik]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/\u0268/}}\n| ''\u1ef1''<br>{{IPA|[\u0268]}} || ''\u1ef1i''<br>{{IPA|[\u0268j]}} || ''\u1ef1u''<br>{{IPA|[\u0268w]}} || || || ''\u1ef1ng''<br>{{IPA|[\u0268\u014b]}} || || ''\u1ef1t''<br>{{IPA|[\u0268t]}} || ''\u1ef1c''<br>{{IPA|[\u0268k]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/u/}}\n| ''\u1ee5''<br>{{IPA|[u]}} || ''\u1ee5i''<br>{{IPA|[uj]}} || || ''\u1ee5m''<br>{{IPA|[um]}} || ''\u1ee5n''<br>{{IPA|[un]}} || ''\u1ee5ng''<br>{{IPA|[u\u014b]}} || ''\u1ee5p''<br>{{IPA|[up]}} || ''\u1ee5t''<br>{{IPA|[ut]}} || ''\u1ee5c''<br>{{IPA|[uk]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/i\u0259/}}\n| ''\u1ecba'', ''(g)\u1ecba'', ''\u1ef5a''<br>{{IPA|[i\u0259]}} || || ''i\u1ec7u'', ''y\u1ec7u''<br>{{IPA|[i\u0259w]}} || ''i\u1ec7m'', ''y\u1ec7m''<br>{{IPA|[i\u0259m]}} || ''i\u1ec7n'', ''y\u1ec7n ''<br>{{IPA|[i\u0259n]}} || ''i\u1ec7ng'', ''y\u1ec7ng''<br>{{IPA|[i\u0259\u014b]}} || ''i\u1ec7p'', ''y\u1ec7p''<br>{{IPA|[i\u0259p]}} || ''i\u1ec7t'', ''y\u1ec7t''<br>{{IPA|[i\u0259t]}} || ''i\u1ec7c''<br>{{IPA|[i\u0259k]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/\u0268\u0259/}}\n| ''\u1ef1a''<br>{{IPA|[\u0268\u0259]}} || ''\u01b0\u1ee3i''<br>{{IPA|[\u0268\u0259j]}} || ''\u01b0\u1ee3u''<br>{{IPA|[\u0268\u0259w]}} || ''\u01b0\u1ee3m''<br>{{IPA|[\u0268\u0259m]}} || ''\u01b0\u1ee3n''<br>{{IPA|[\u0268\u0259n]}} || ''\u01b0\u1ee3ng''<br>{{IPA|[\u0268\u0259\u014b]}} || ''\u01b0\u1ee3p''<br>{{IPA|[\u0268\u0259p]}} || ''\u01b0\u1ee3t''<br>{{IPA|[\u0268\u0259t]}} || ''\u01b0\u1ee3c''<br>{{IPA|[\u0268\u0259k]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/u\u0259/}}\n| ''\u1ee5a''<br>{{IPA|[u\u0259]}} || ''u\u1ed9i''<br>{{IPA|[u\u0259j]}} || || ''u\u1ed9m''<br>{{IPA|[u\u0259m]}} || ''u\u1ed9n''<br>{{IPA|[u\u0259n]}} || ''u\u1ed9ng''<br>{{IPA|[u\u0259\u014b]}} || || ''u\u1ed9t''<br>{{IPA|[u\u0259t]}} || ''u\u1ed9c''<br>{{IPA|[u\u0259k]}}\n|-\n! rowspan=\"8\" | Labiovelar on-glide followed by vowel nucleus\n! {{IPA|/\u02b7\u0103/}}\n| || ''o\u1ea1y'', ''(q)u\u1ea1y''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7\u0103j]}} || || ''o\u1eb7m'', ''(q)u\u1eb7m''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7\u0103m]}} || ''o\u1eb7n'', ''(q)u\u1eb7n''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7\u0103n]}} || ''o\u1eb7ng'', ''(q)u\u1eb7ng''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7\u0103\u014b]}} || ''o\u1eb7p'', ''(q)u\u1eb7p''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7\u0103p]}} || ''o\u1eb7t'', ''(q)u\u1eb7t''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7\u0103t]}} || ''o\u1eb7c'', ''(q)u\u1eb7c''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7\u0103k]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/\u02b7a/}}\n| ''o\u1ea1'', ''(q)u\u1ea1''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7a]}} || ''o\u1ea1i'', ''(q)u\u1ea1i''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7aj]}} || ''o\u1ea1o'', ''(q)u\u1ea1o''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7aw]}} || ''o\u1ea1m'', ''(q)u\u1ea1m''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7am]}} || ''o\u1ea1n'', ''(q)u\u1ea1n''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7an]}} || ''o\u1ea1ng'', ''(q)u\u1ea1ng ''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7a\u014b]}} || ''o\u1ea1p'', ''(q)u\u1ea1p''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7ap]}} || ''o\u1ea1t'', ''(q)u\u1ea1t''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7at]}} || ''o\u1ea1c'', ''(q)u\u1ea1c''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7ak]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/\u02b7\u025b/}}\n| ''o\u1eb9'', ''(q)u\u1eb9''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7\u025b]}} || || ''o\u1eb9o'', ''(q)u\u1eb9o''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7\u025bw]}} || ''o\u1eb9m'', ''(q)u\u1eb9m''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7\u025bm]}} || ''o\u1eb9n'', ''(q)u\u1eb9n''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7\u025bn]}} || ''o\u1ea1nh'', ''(q)u\u1ea1nh''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7\u0103j\u014b]}} || || ''o\u1eb9t'', ''(q)u\u1eb9t''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7\u025bt]}} || ''o\u1ea1ch'', ''(q)u\u1ea1ch''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7\u0103jk]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/\u02b7\u0259\u0306/}}\n| || ''u\u1eady''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7\u0259\u0306j]}} || || || ''u\u1eadn''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7\u0259\u0306n]}} || ''u\u1eadng''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7\u0259\u0306\u014b]}} || || ''u\u1eadt''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7\u0259\u0306t]}} ||\n|-\n! {{IPA|/\u02b7\u0259/}}\n| ''u\u1ee3''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7\u0259]}} || || || || || || || ||\n|-\n! {{IPA|/\u02b7e/}}\n| ''u\u1ec7''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7e]}} || || ''u\u1ec7u''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7ew]}} || || ''u\u1ec7n''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7en]}} || ''u\u1ec7nh''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7\u0259\u0306j\u014b]}} || || ''u\u1ec7t''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7et]}} || ''u\u1ec7ch''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7\u0259\u0306jk]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/\u02b7i/}}\n| ''u\u1ef5''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7i]}} || || ''u\u1ef5u''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7iw]}} || || ''u\u1ef5n''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7in]}} || ''u\u1ef5nh''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7i\u014b]}} || ''u\u1ef5p''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7ip]}} || ''u\u1ef5t''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7it]}} || ''u\u1ef5ch''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7ik]}}\n|-\n! {{IPA|/\u02b7i\u0259/}}\n| ''u\u1ef5a''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7i\u0259]}} || || || || ''uy\u1ec7n''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7i\u0259n]}} || || || ''uy\u1ec7t''<br>{{IPA|[\u02b7i\u0259t]}} ||\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Tone\n! colspan=\"6\" | ''a'' {{IPA|/a/}}, ''\u00e0'' {{IPA|/\u00e2/}}, ''\u00e1'' {{IPA|/\u01ce/}}, ''\u1ea3'' {{IPA|/a\u1dc9/}}, ''\u00e3'' {{IPA|/\u01ce\u02c0/}}, ''\u1ea1'' {{IPA|/\u00e2\u02c0/}}\n! colspan=\"3\" | ''\u00e1'' {{IPA|/\u00e1/}}, ''\u1ea1'' {{IPA|/\u00e0/}}\n|}\n{{refbegin}}\n{{note|Notes| Notes:}}\n* Less common rimes may not be represented in this table.\n* The ''n\u1eb7ng'' tone mark (dot below) has been added to all rimes in this table for illustration purposes only. It indicates which letter tone marks in general are added to, largely according to the \"new style\" rules of Vietnamese orthography as stated in [[:vi:Quy t\u1eafc \u0111\u1eb7t d\u1ea5u thanh trong ch\u1eef qu\u1ed1c ng\u1eef#Ki.E1.BB.83u m.E1.BB.9Bi|Quy t\u1eafc \u0111\u1eb7t d\u1ea5u thanh trong ch\u1eef qu\u1ed1c ng\u1eef]]. In practice, not all these rimes have real words or syllables that have the ''n\u1eb7ng'' tone.\n* The IPA representations are based on [[Help:IPA/Vietnamese|Wikipedia's conventions]]. Different dialects may have different pronunciations.\n{{refend}}\n\n==Notes==\n:{{note label|monophthongs|2|2}}\n\nBelow is a table comparing four linguists' different transcriptions of Vietnamese vowels as well as the orthographic representation. Notice that this article mostly follows {{Harvcoltxt|Han|1966}}, with the exception of marking short vowels short.\n\n:{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ comparison of orthography & vowel descriptions\n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n! Orthography\n! Wikipedia\n! Thompson<ref name=\"Harvcoltxt|Thompson|1965\">{{Harvcoltxt|Thompson|1965}}</ref>\n! Han<ref name=\"Harvcoltxt|Han|1966\"/>\n! Nguy\u1ec5n<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Nguy\u1ec5n|1997}}</ref>\n! \u0110o\u00e0n<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|\u0110o\u00e0n|1980}}</ref>\n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| i/y\n| {{IPA|i}}\n| {{IPA|i\u02d0}}\n| {{IPA|i}}\n| {{IPA|i}}\n| {{IPA|i}}\n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| \u00ea\n| {{IPA|e}}\n| {{IPA|e\u02d0}}\n| {{IPA|e}}\n| {{IPA|e}}\n| {{IPA|e}}\n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| e\n| {{IPA|\u025b}}\n| {{IPA|\u025b\u02d0}}\n| {{IPA|\u025b}}\n| {{IPA|a}}\n| {{IPA|\u025b}}\n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| \u01b0\n| {{IPA|\u0268}}\n| {{IPA|\u026f\u02d0}}\n| {{IPA|\u0268}}\n| {{IPA|\u026f}}\n| {{IPA|\u026f}}\n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| u\n| {{IPA|u}}\n| {{IPA|u\u02d0}}\n| {{IPA|u}}\n| {{IPA|u}}\n| {{IPA|u}}\n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| \u00f4\n| {{IPA|o}}\n| {{IPA|o\u02d0}}\n| {{IPA|o}}\n| {{IPA|o}}\n| {{IPA|o}}\n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| o\n| {{IPA|\u0254}}\n| {{IPA|\u0254\u02d0}}\n| {{IPA|\u0254}}\n| {{IPA|\u0254}}\n| {{IPA|\u0254}}\n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| \u01a1\n| {{IPA|\u0259}}\n| {{IPA|\u0264\u02d0}}\n| {{IPA|\u025c\u02d0}}\n| {{IPA|\u0259\u02d0}}\n| {{IPA|\u0264\u02d0}}\n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| \u00e2\n| {{IPA|\u0259\u0306}}\n| {{IPA|\u028c}}\n| {{IPA|\u025c}}\n| {{IPA|\u0259}}\n| {{IPA|\u0264}}\n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| a\n| {{IPA|a}}\n| {{IPA|\u00e6\u02d0}}\n| {{IPA|\u0250\u02d0}}\n| {{IPA|\u0250\u02d0}}\n| {{IPA|a\u02d0}}\n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| \u0103\n| {{IPA|\u0103}}\n| {{IPA|\u0250}}\n| {{IPA|\u0250}}\n| {{IPA|\u0250}}\n| {{IPA|a}}\n|}\n\n{{Harvcoltxt|Thompson|1965}} says that the vowels {{IPA|[\u028c]}} (orthographic '''\u00e2''') and {{IPA|[\u0250]}} (orthographic '''\u0103''') are shorter than all of the other vowels, which is shown here with the length mark {{IPA|[\u02d0]}} added to the other vowels. His vowels above are only the basic vowel phonemes. Thompson gives a very detailed description of each vowel's various allophonic realizations.\n\n{{Harvcoltxt|Han|1966}} uses acoustic analysis, including [[spectrogram]]s and [[formant]] measuring and plotting, to describe the vowels. She states that the primary difference between orthographic ''\u01a1'' & ''\u00e2'' and ''a'' & ''\u0103'' is a difference of length (a ratio of 2:1).  ''\u01a1'' = {{IPA|/\u025c\u02d0/}}, ''\u00e2'' = {{IPA|/\u025c/}}; ''a'' = {{IPA|/\u0250\u02d0/}}, ''\u0103'' = {{IPA|/\u0250/}}. Her formant plots also seem to show that {{IPA|/\u025c\u02d0/}} may be slightly higher than {{IPA|/\u025c/}} in some contexts (but this would be secondary to the main difference of length).\n\nAnother thing to mention about Han's studies is that she uses a rather small number of participants and, additionally, although her participants are native speakers of the Hanoi variety, they all have lived outside of Hanoi for a significant period of their lives (e.g. in [[France]] or [[Ho Chi Minh City]]).\n\n{{Harvcoltxt|Nguy\u1ec5n|1997}} has a simpler, more symmetrical description. He says that his work is not a \"complete grammar\" but rather a \"descriptive introduction.\"  So, his chart above is more a phonological vowel chart rather than a phonetic one.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n*Alves, Mark J. 2007. \"A Look At North-Central Vietnamese.\" In ''SEALS XII Papers from the 12th Annual Meeting of the Southeast Asian Linguistics Society 2002'', edited by Ratree Wayland et al.. Canberra, Australia, 1\u20137. Pacific Linguistics, Research School of Pacific and Asian Studies, The Australian National University. [http://sealang.net/sala/archives/pdf8/alves2002look.pdf]\n* {{citation\n|last=Brunelle\n|first=Marc\n|year=2003\n|chapter=Coarticulation effects in northern Vietnamese tones\n|chapter-url=http://aix1.uottawa.ca/~mbrunell/Viet%20coarticulation.pdf\n|title=Proceedings of the 15th International Conference of Phonetic Sciences\n}}\n* {{citation\n|last=Brunelle\n|first=Marc\n|year=2009\n|title=Tone perception in Northern and Southern Vietnamese\n|journal=Journal of Phonetics\n|volume=37\n|issue=1\n|pages=79\u201396\n|doi=10.1016/j.wocn.2008.09.003\n}}\n* {{citation\n|last=\u0110o\u00e0n\n|first=Thi\u1ec7n Thu\u1eadt\n|year=1980\n|title=Ng\u1eef \u00e2m ti\u1ebfng Vi\u1ec7t\n|place=[[Hanoi|H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i]]\n|publisher=\u0110\u1ea1i h\u1ecdc v\u00e0 Trung h\u1ecdc Chuy\u00ean nghi\u1ec7p\n}}\n* \u0110o\u00e0n, Thi\u1ec7n Thu\u1eadt; Nguy\u1ec5n, Kh\u00e1nh H\u00e0, Ph\u1ea1m, Nh\u01b0 Qu\u1ef3nh. (2003). ''A Concise Vietnamese Grammar (For Non-Native Speakers)''. H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i: Th\u1ebf Gi\u1edbi Publishers, 2001.\n* Earle, M. A. (1975). ''An acoustic study of northern Vietnamese tones''. Santa Barbara: Speech Communications Research Laboratory, Inc.\n* {{citation\n|last=Emerich\n|first=Giang Huong\n|year=2012\n|title=The Vietnamese Vowel System\n|url=https://repository.upenn.edu/edissertations/632/\n|series=Publicly Accessible Penn Dissertations\n|publisher=University of Pennsylvania\n}}\n* Ferlus, Michel. (1997). Problemes de la formation du systeme vocalique du vietnamien. ''Asie Orientale'', ''26'' (1), .\n* Gregerson, Kenneth J. (1969). A study of Middle Vietnamese phonology. ''Bulletin de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des Etudes Indochinoises'', ''44'', 135\u2013193. (Published version of the author's MA thesis, University of Washington). (Reprinted 1981, Dallas: Summer Institute of Linguistics).\n* {{citation\n|last=Han\n|first=Mieko\n|year=1966\n|title=Vietnamese vowels\n|series=Studies in the phonology of Asian languages\n|volume=4\n|place=Los Angeles: Acoustic Phonetics Research Laboratory\n|publisher=University of S